 Description:
 The Mortar Fire Control System (MFCS) accurately determines weapon position and orientation, navigates, calculates ballistics, and communicates digitally on the Fire Support Network. MFCS improves the
 accuracy of the 120mm mortar system from 138 meters Circular Error Probable (CEP) to 75 meters CEP allowing for first round fire for effect. MFCS increases survivability of mortar crews by eliminating the need
 for soldiers to dismount the vehicle to lay out aiming posts. MFCS also adds digital connectivity to Joint Battle Command-Platform (JBC-P). MFCS consists of the M95/M96 versions that are used on mounted
 120mm Mortar systems in the Armored Brigade Combat Teams (ABCTs), the Stryker Brigade Combat Teams (SBCTs), and the M150/M151 versions used on the M120A1 120mm Towed Mortar systems that
 are fielded throughout all Mobile Brigade Combat Teams (MBCTs). Both the M95 and M150 consist of five main components: 1) Fire Control Computer (FCC), which links the MFCS components together,
 communicates, and calculates the ballistic solutions; 2) Tactical Advanced Land Inertial Navigator (TALIN), which is the pointing device and position system that provides the weapon's position, pointing azimuth
 and elevation; 3) Gunner's Display (GD), which shows the gunner where to point the tube and displays the weapon's azimuth, elevation, and ballistic firing solution; 4) Driver's Display (DD), used with the M95
 only, which provides a "steer-to" display to aid in navigation and emplacement of the vehicle; and 5) Power Distribution Assembly/Enhanced Power Distribution Assembly, which filters vehicle power and acts as a
 circuit breaker by isolating MFCS line replaceable units from power fluctuations and surges.
