 Description:
 Program Overview:

 The Defense Counterintelligence and Security Agency (DCSA) Zero Trust (ZT) program is designed in support of the President's Executive Order on Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity (EO 14028) and
 National Security Memorandum 8 (NSM-8) that directs the Federal Civilian Executive Branch agencies and National Security System (NSS) owners to develop and implement plans to adopt ZT and Identity,
 Credential and Access Management (ICAM) cybersecurity & architecture capabilities.

 Justification:
 The funding will ensure compliance of Department of War (DoW) Directives, and the FY2024 NDAA mandate adoption of ZT principles across federal agencies. Implementing a ZT architecture is important as it
 alters the security approach by assuming that breaches may occur and necessitating ongoing verification of every user, device, and application seeking access to resources. By executing micro-segmentation,
 enforcing least-privilege access, and leveraging continuous monitoring, we can significantly reduce the attack surface, limit the blast radius of potential breaches, and detect and respond to threats more
 effectively. Without this funding, DCSA remains vulnerable to devastating data breaches, which could compromise national security, damage our reputation, and result in significant financial losses, including
 potential legal and regulatory penalties.

 DCSA no longer requires PROC funding in FY27due to the new agency IT Strategy and transformation efforts. The funding is realigned to O&M.




