 Justification:
 CYBER THREAT EMULATION SYSTEM AND TOOLS ($14.282M)
 • Funding procures hardware and tools that enable the DCDC and Joint Operations Centers to conduct network vulnerability inspections and threat emulation activities essential to joint cyberspace
 missions. These capabilities strengthen the Department of War's defensive posture by improving enterprise visibility and enabling proactive identification of cyber weaknesses.

 • The FY 2027 request includes $1.465M for technology refresh across the Joint Worldwide Intelligence Communication System (JWICS), Non-classified Internet Protocol Router Network (NIPRnet), and Secret
 Internet Protocol Router Network (SIPRnet). These upgrades are required to maintain continuous support to defensive cyber operations and ensure the Joint Defense Operations Center can sustain real time
 situational awareness across DCDC's operational area.

 • An additional $12.000M expands the Department of War's vulnerability-visualization capability, enabling an outside-in assessment of the Department of War Information Network. This enhancement improves
 the ability of Cybersecurity Service Providers to identify, prioritize, and mitigate vulnerabilities based on operational risk and adversary targeting behavior.

 DATA AND SENSORS ($78,599M):
 • Funding provides the data, sensing, and deployable capabilities required for Cyber Protection Teams (CPTs) and DCDC to detect, analyze, and counter advanced cyber threats across the global Department of
 War networks. Resources procure and field Joint Cyber Hunt Kits (JCHKs), which deliver the computing power, storage, and specialized tools necessary for rapid deployment and full-spectrum hunt operations on
 high-risk and forward-deployed networks.

 • Prototype testing for the Joint Cyber Hunt Kit concluded in FY 2025, with vendor selection completed in early FY 2026. FY 2026 activities include development of training and accreditation kits and award of
 the production contract. In FY 2027, procurement supports production and delivery of 74 additional kits to the Service Cyber Components and the Cyber National Mission Force, enabling transition from legacy
 systems, standardizing capabilities, and expanding global hunt capacity.

 • The FY 2027 request includes a $30.100M increase to accelerate procurement as USCYBERCOM centralizes acquisition and standardizes kit design. This acceleration is required to meet validated demand,
 achieve cost and sustainment efficiencies, and replace legacy kits before they become unsupportable

 ROBUST INFRASTRUCTURE AND ACCESS ($10.974M):




