 Justification:
 Teleport:

 FY 2025: $25.848 million - DoW Teleport replaced End-of-Life (EOL) equipment and fielded enhancements at Teleport SATCOM sites. There were 400+ devices at seven sites that required refresh. Major
 efforts included iDirect tech refresh and crypto modernization, fielding and operationalization of seven allied Mobile User Objective System (MUOS) to Legacy Gateway Components (MLGCs) at seven Satellite
 Communications (SATCOM) Gateways. This funding addressed performance, cyber, and maintainability issues for fielded Teleport Systems by installing, integrating, and fielding next-generation technologies
 which increased capabilities, service life, reliability, and resiliency. DISA also created a standard architecture between Teleport and SATCOM sites.

 • Teleport: Hardware, Install, Check, Initial training, Spares: $13.272 million - Conducted the annual tech refresh of eleven sites worldwide.
 • Teleport: Program Management and System Engineering support for Teleport: $2.240 million - Provided contractor support for Teleport technology refresh. Activities included scheduling,
 procuring, testing, installing, and implementing new devices so that the warfighter could communicate and access the Defense Information Systems Network (DISN) across the globe.
 • Integrated Waveform (IW): $10.336 million - Installed, integrated, and enhanced the three of the seven allied MLGCs to complement the U.S. MLGC sub-system. This is a continuation of the FY 2024 effort.
 Seven sites were originally planned but delays associated with site Military Construction (MILCON)
 efforts, extended failover testing, and equipment tech refresh timing resulted in four sites being deferred to FY 2026.

 FY 2026: $25.911 million - DoW Teleport replaces End-of-Life (EoL) equipment and field enhancements at Teleport SATCOM sites. There are now 500+ devices at 16 combined Teleport sites that require tech
 refresh. Teleport, Standardized Tactical Entry Point (STEP), and SATCOM programs were using similar equipment (e.g., modems, satellite dishes) at overlapping locations. DISA decided to consolidate the three
 programs so they could draw on a common set of equipment of common locations. This resulted in the number of Teleport sites increasing to 16. DISA is able to draw on legacy STEP and SATCOM funding
 profiles to support the tech refresh needs of these additional sites.

 Major efforts for FY 2026 include SATCOM earth terminal Radio Frequency (RF) equipment and system server tech refresh, Teleport convergence routers, switches, firewalls, modems, and encryption devices.
 This funding addresses performance, cyber, and maintainability issues for the fielded Teleport Systems, thereby improving service life, reliability, and resiliency of the fielded systems. DISA also fields and
 operationalizes four additional allied MLGCs at Joint SATCOM Teleport sites for seven total operational allied MLGCs.

 • Teleport: Hardware, Install, Check, Initial training, Spares –Teleport Sites: $19.458 million - Conduct annual tech refresh of 16 Teleport Sites worldwide based on tech refresh plans. A key project in
 FY 2026 involves the replacement of earth modems across the Teleport network. This is an extensive replacement that requires purchasing earth modems for all sites.
 • Teleport: Program Management and System Engineering support for combined Teleport/SATCOM Gateway/STEP portfolio: $2.500 million - Provide contractor support for tech refresh.

