 Description:
 The Defense Information Systems Network (DISN) is the DoW consolidated global telecommunications infrastructure. It provides end-to-end information transport for DoW operations, empowering warfighters
 and Combatant Commanders through its Command, Control, Communications, Computers, and Intelligence (C4I) long-haul network. Seamlessly spanning terrestrial to space and strategic to tactical domains,
 the DISN delivers interoperable telecommunications connectivity. This enables the planning, implementation, and support of all operational missions at any time. DISN services extend to the network's edge,
 providing warfighters worldwide access. The DISN forms a platform for DoW's core communications, computing, and information services. It integrates terrestrial, subsea, wireless, mobile, and satellite
 communications into a network cloud that is survivable and dynamically scalable.

 DISN Procurement funding supports the following core areas:

 • The Enhanced Pentagon Capability (EPC)/Survivable Emergency Conferencing Network (SECN): The EPC/SECN delivers classified communication capabilities vital for senior leaders. It strictly adheres to
 the stringent requirements outlined in Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Instruction (CJCSI) 6811.01B, the Nuclear Technical Performance Criteria (NTPC). Consequently, the EPC network must maintain
 uninterrupted availability and peak performance.

 • Airborne Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance Data Transport (AISR-DT): AISR-DT supports Combatant Commands, Services, and Agencies (CC/S/A) by gathering, analyzing, and streaming AISR
 sensor data to globally dispersed strategic, operational, and tactical customers. The timely and assured delivery of this fused intelligence provides information superiority crucial for Counterterrorism, Theater
 Campaign Plans, and Contingency Operations.

 • AISR-Resilient Ground Infrastructure (RGI): Airborne Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance Ground Entry Points (GEPs) receive sensor data from Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS) and other aircraft.
 This data is then transmitted to deployed warfighters, directly enhancing their effectiveness and lethality. UAS have long served as a highly effective means of observing tactical battlespaces, providing near real-
 time battlefield awareness of threats and adversarial actions across various military operations.

 Recognizing the dependency on these systems, the Department of War Chief Information Officer (DoW CIO) commissioned the Gateway Optimization and Resiliency (GOaR) Study. Finalized and accepted
 by the DoW CIO in July 2022, the study's objective was to assess the overall resiliency of the entire DoW Satellite Communication (SATCOM) Enterprise, with a specific focus on the sufficiency of its ground
 infrastructure. The GOaR Study concluded that the DoW must significantly improve the technological capabilities of its DoW Information Network (DoWIN) GEPs. This includes increasing the capacity of each



