 Description:
 The White House Communication Agency (WHCA) provides communication and information technology services to the President of the United States (POTUS), Vice President of the United States (VPOTUS),
 White House Staff, National Security Staff (NSS), U.S. Secret Service (USSS), and others as directed by the White House Military Office (WHMO) and the White House Director of Technology.

 WHCA maintains and modernizes the White House communications infrastructure. It serves as the information technology (IT) provider for White House organizations across the National Capital Region (NCR).
 These organizations include Presidential Airlift Group (PAG)/Air Force One, Presidential Helicopter Squadron/Marine One, Camp David, the White House Transportation Agency, Presidential Mess, Medical
 Unit, Military Aides, Second Residences, Continuity of Government (COG)/Continuity of Operations (COOP) sites, and all Executive Office of the President offices via the Presidential Information Technology
 Community (PITC) network.

 WHCA provides the President the ability to communicate securely, anywhere, anytime, by any means, to anyone. It modernizes and integrates communication technologies requested by its customers. Given
 their national security missions, its customers require tools that operate on-demand and in all conditions. Modernization efforts improve the White House's ability to protect national security and respond to events
 and crises. These efforts involve replacing obsolete IT capabilities (End-of-Life (EoL) and/or end-of-service support) with new equipment that adapts to evolving technology. WHCA modernizes technologies that
 enhance the President's communication capabilities, ensure command and control, and establish an information sharing domain within the PITC at all classification levels.

 The President's ability to communicate securely in all situations is vital. This ensures the Commander-in-Chief can lead forces to respond to threats in real time. WHCA aims to maintain communication across
 all infrastructures at a 100 percent effective rate. This reflects its "no-fail" national security mission. Prioritizing technological advancement helps maintain an advantage over cybersecurity threats. WHCA
 continuously provides services to POTUS, VPOTUS, NSS, USSS, WHMO, and the White House Director of Technology through four core portfolios: Broadcast and Audio-Visual Services, Senior Leadership
 Communications, Enterprise IT, and Deployable Services.




