 Justification:
 FY 2025: $100.587 million:

 Broadcast and Audio-Visual Services: $4.886 million - The White House Communication Agency (WHCA) provided voice, video, and image support for the President (POTUS), Vice President (VPOTUS), and
 other designated leaders. Its portfolio included Audio-Visual Capabilities Support, Broadcast Production, the Presidential Broadcast Archive, and Multimedia Production. WHCA administered services that served
 as the communication interface to the American and international public and press, ensuring national leaders could communicate globally via any broadcast media. WHCA acquired Information Technology
 (IT) equipment to support historical records and custom broadcast products, including digital, visual, and graphic services, unified communications, increased bandwidth, on-demand services, enhanced
 multimedia use, and real-time broadcast and streaming. The portfolio added smart tagging for global access and search. Upgrades modernized and automated Master Control, Presidential Records archiving,
 and accessibility to support post-production storage, reporting, and public dissemination. WHCA evolved and modernized multimedia services and production for government, news, and other organizations to
 record and stream events.

 Senior Leader Communications and Transport Services: $27.185 million - WHCA invested in six technological capabilities supporting telecommunications, Command and Control (C2), and messaging services
 for the President, Vice President, National Security Staff (NSS), White House Military Office (WHMO) leadership, U.S. Secret Service (USSS), and other designated senior national leaders, maintaining 99.99
 percent equipment availability. The agency evolved and consolidated on-demand network backbone infrastructure and unified Internet Protocol (IP) and next-generation network services. WHCA provided
 storage, virtualization, and collaborative tools to WHMO/WHCA. WHCA adopted DoW Senior National Leadership Command and Control (NLCC) Communications recommendations to ensure communications
 met WHCA's Primary Alternate Contingency Emergency requirements, including Continuity of Government (COG) and Continuity of Operations (COOP). WHCA delivered reliable, secure, and modern Senior
 Leader Communication capabilities, providing timely, critically protected information to the POTUS, VPOTUS, and their support and protection teams, regardless of location. WHCA provided national-level
 classified conferencing and continuity of support for the President in permanent or temporary locations, ground transportation, or aboard fixed-wing and rotary-wing aircraft. WHCA leveraged new commercial
 solutions for enhanced capabilities, including Presidential Unified Motorcade Communication (PUMC) linking key motorcade vehicles, mobile Voice Video and Visualization, Virtual Personal Assistant, post-Zero-
 Day recovery, and next-generation networking. Additionally, WHCA upgraded SATCOM channels between the White House Campus and other sites in the National Capital Region (NCR).

 WHCA invested in three additional Transport capabilities that provided global, point-to-point connectivity between mission partners, enhancing the Presidential Transport Network supporting Senior Leader
 Communications, Broadcast, and Audio-Visual services. The portfolio offered global connectivity between dispersed partners via Wireless, Synchronous Optical Network (SONET), Wide Area Network (WAN),
 and Internet Protocol (IP). This service utilized a mix of government-owned and commercially leased, secure, highly available, assured, and resilient circuits, wireless, and satellite capabilities to support Senior
 National Leadership during both routine operations and emergencies. WHCA leveraged emerging network transport, wireless, and satellite technologies to build a Multi-Level System (MLS) backbone supporting
 secure unified communications, voice, video, visualization, and high-speed transport. The agency evaluated DoW/DISA and commercial wireless and satellite solutions (e.g., FirstNet, SpaceX, Mobile User
 Objective System (MUOS), Free Space Optics, 5G, and Iridium). WHCA enhanced the Presidential Transport Network, extending Presidential Information Technology Community (PITC) Enterprise services and
 capabilities to customers.

 Note: WHCA executed Transport funding as a sub portfolio of Senior Leadership Communications in FY 2025: nine total capabilities supported in the combined portfolio.




