 Justification:
 FY 2025: $57.877 million:

 Joint Service Provider (JSP) (J6 Pentagon) Pentagon/National Capital Region (NCR) Information Technology (IT) Modernization: $40.061 million - Enabled modernization and replacement of outdated
 technologies and capabilities in support of Pentagon/NCR Common IT operations. Capabilities supported the Office of the Secretary of War (SECWAR), the Joint Staff, Headquarters Department of the Army,
 on-boarded 4th Estate IT organizations, as well as tenants in the Pentagon, Mark Center, and other supported leased-facilities across the NCR. In FY 2025, JSP focused primarily on lifecycle replacement
 and modernization of network infrastructure, funding eleven projects aligned to Transport. Additionally, Phase 2 of a Voice, Data, and Video Modernization/Replacement project was funded. As JSP finalized
 requirements and awarded contracts in the year of execution, JSP found the flexibility to tackle more projects than originally envisioned.

 Major lines of effort covered under this activity included:

 • Transport: $38.422 million - Efforts to modernize the network included expanding the Software Defined Network (SDN) and replacing legacy Pentagon Wedge Routers with updated equipment, including critical
 cabling in the Pentagon and NCR, to improve customer experience. A Mark Center Protective Distribution System (PDS) refresh and Pentagon switch modernization initiative further replaced aging devices,
 promoting redundancy and mitigating security, performance, and accreditation risks. The ten projects funded included SDN expansion, Wedge Upgrade & Modernization, Mark Center PDS lifecycle refresh,
 Pentagon Switch upgrade modernization, Pentagon Primary Technical Control Facility (PPTCF) tech refresh, Encryption Modernization investment, JSP Wi-Fi Network security, Phase 2 of the Mission Integrated
 System Software Enterprise Environment (MISSEE) project, Phase 2 of the Network Access Point-C (NAP-C) Modernization, and a classified Local Area Network project.

 • Voice, Data, and Video Modernization and Replacement: $1.639 million - Phase 2 of a voice project supported migration of voice and video services to enterprise collaboration offerings, refreshed legacy Audio-
 Visual (AV) and Video-Teleconference (VTC) hardware and software, and migrated to soft clients for Voice and Video service delivery.

 Secretary of War Communications (SWC) Critical Infrastructure Modernization: $6.816 million - Included the procurement of critical IT equipment (mobility, hardware and software tools, crypto) that provided
 critical business operations, high-availability architecture, and core infrastructure support to the Office of the Secretary of War Communications. The upgrades ensured critical, dedicated, and secure access to
 multi-path, resilient, and highly reliable communications capabilities, consistent with the mandated National Leadership Command Capability (NLCC) responsibilities.

 • Mobile, Voice, Desktop and Video Modernization/Replacement: $6.753 million - Provided phased modernization/lifecycle refresh of AV and VTC hardware and software in the Secretary of War's Global
 Situational Awareness Facility conference rooms and the cables watch floor to fully integrate modernized AV/VTC capabilities for the Secretary of War. This modernization also supported Executive
 Communications Vehicle (ECV) lifecycle refresh and extended voice, video, and data communications at all levels of classification on a mobile, land-based platform providing uninterrupted Command and Control
 capabilities for the Secretary of War. The two initiatives that supported this LOE were: AV and Teleconference Modernization and ECV.

 • Communication Security: $0.063 million - Provided enhanced cybersecurity capabilities with Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) hardware and software in alignment with DISA's ZTA implementation goal. The one
 initiative that supported this LOE was ZTA tools.



