 Justification:
 FY 2025: $24.482 million:

 DoDNet Equipment/Agency Migration Support - Many Defense Agencies and Field Activities (DAFAs) did not have DoDNet compliant infrastructure. The DoDNet Program Management Office (PMO) conducted
 site surveys to determine the level of tech refresh required at each agency. Then, the DoDNet PMO conducted a tech refresh to create an environment suitable for DoDNet migration. Costs associated with tech
 refresh and replacement varied due to the size of the DAFA and the quality of the current equipment. FY 2025 included the following activities:

 • Acquired network infrastructure hardware to upgrade/tech refresh outdated equipment at multiple DAFA site locations. Modernized infrastructure requirements were determined by the number of DAFAs, site
 sizes, cabling/integration, design and install of all-new network equipment. After deployment and integration, this effort consolidated multiple networks into a single, centrally managed network.

 • Conducted tech refreshes of outdated, end-of-life equipment to standardize network infrastructure, improve network cybersecurity, and strengthen network resilience across the DoDNet environment. This
 hardware also supported network monitoring capabilities critical for network discovery and service performance. These capabilities helped to identify and mitigate service issues quickly. The deployment of
 hardware, software, and network monitoring capabilities provided the ability to adjust to changes in DoW/Agency priorities and needs. These tools also reduced the growth of redundant Information Technology
 (IT) systems and increased the visibility of all network-connected devices.

 • Procured hardware replaced outdated equipment with updated tools that can be integrated into the DoDNet environment. During FY 2025, DoDNet PMO oversaw 13 active DAFA migrations. With the new
 strategy, 1,402 users migrated to DoDNet. The DoDNet PMO purchased network hardware and software to migrate agencies to DoDNet securely and safely.

 DoDNet Service Centers:

 • Purchased hardware to equip six Service Centers with new servers, which connect various DoW Agencies to the DoDNet interface. New hardware strengthened DoDNet Service Center capabilities to provide
 seamless connectivity to DoDNet. Continual work was needed to ensure that Service Centers can handle additional user workloads. Otherwise, DoW personnel's user experience would have been downgraded
 significantly. This upgrade also facilitated the deployment of the Thunderdome enhanced Zero Trust security capability.

 Lifecycle Refresh for Migrated Agencies - DAFAs required lifecycle technical replacements to keep networks operating effectively and securely after successful migration. Replacements began in FY 2025 of
 equipment purchased to support the initial migrations.

 • Conducted lifecycle technical refresh of agencies already migrated to DoDNet after four years. DoDNet is on a five-year equipment replacement lifecycle that starts four years after the equipment is purchased.
 Replacement of equipment began in FY 2025 for the three initial agencies already migrated to DoDNet. The first year of tech refresh averaged 40 percent completion across the board and will achieve 100
 percent by the five-year lifecycle replacement mark.

 FY 2026: $75.386 million:

