 Description:
 The Defense Threat Reduction Agency (DTRA) executes critical national security missions to counter weapons of mass destruction (WMD) threats through advanced technologies, methodologies, and
 capabilities development. This program supports DTRA's operational requirements to deter strategic attacks against the United States and its Allies; prevent, reduce, and counter WMD and emerging chemical,
 biological, radiological, and nuclear (CBRN) threats; and enable mission success against WMD-armed adversaries across the spectrum of crisis and conflict scenarios. This budget line-item funds vehicle
 procurement and lifecycle management through General Services Administration (GSA) and other authorized acquisition channels. Cost is driven by operational requirements, which encompass terrain
 accessibility, specialized support needs, and geographical location. Austere terrain operations accelerate wear, reduce lifespan, and increase maintenance demands. Fleet management and maintenance
 operations align with established GSA guidelines and federal vehicle lifecycle standards. Future Year Defense Program (FYDP) projections support continued lifecycle replacement requirements.

 Misson Requirements supported:

 - CONUS/OCONUS fleet replacement: Lifecycle replacement of aged Agency-owned non-tactical vehicles (NTVs) supporting continental United States and overseas operations.

 - Specialized industrial vehicle support: Lifecycle replacement of specialized industrial trucks ensures mission readiness for a range of critical activities, including WMD response, testing, training, operational
 deployments, and heavy cargo transport across all materiel classifications.

 Justification:
 Sustained funding maintains operational readiness and mission-essential capabilities through systematic vehicle fleet lifecycle management and replacement operations, ensuring compliance with DTRA's
 statutory WMD threat reduction mission and enabling seamless interagency coordination and support.

 The FY 2025 budget of $2.754 million resourced (1) lifecycle replacement of fleet-aged, Agency-owned non-tactical vehicles with specific requirements based on factors such as terrain, special support
 requirements and location and (2) lifecycle replacement of aging specialized industrial trucks at White Sands Missile Range (WSMR) testing facility, New Mexico. FY 2025 quantities: 8 non-tactical vehicles and
 10 specialized industrial trucks.

 The FY 2026 budget of $0.911 million resources (1) lifecycle replacement of fleet-aged, Agency-owned non-tactical vehicles with specific requirements based on factors such as terrain, special support
 requirements and location and (2) lifecycle replacement of aging specialized industrial trucks in support of DTRA programs. FY 2026 quantities: 7 non-tactical vehicles and 3 specialized industrial trucks.

