Justification:
The FY 2025 budget of $8.783 million resourced the following efforts:

- Procured and installed one of two remaining next-generation Noble Gas Systems, upgraded one radionuclide particulate system, and upgraded one radionuclide shelter for the United States and Nuclear Arms
Control Technology (NACT) program to improve detection capability and strengthen the arms control verification regime;

- Modernized the Defense Stockpile Management System (DSMS) network infrastructure with advanced network encryption, cyber and Artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities to enhance security and improve
threat detection;

- Acquired 40 components that comprise the overall Joint Radiation Detection System (RDS) to train Service Members at the Department of War (DoW) Nuclear Weapons School on Kirtland AFB to operate in a
realistic combined joint radiological environment;

- Refreshed (lifecycle replacement) mission infrastructure to maintain 99.9% availability on Non-classified Internet Protocol Router Network (NIPR), Secret Internet Protocol Router Network (SIPR), and Joint
Worldwide Intelligence Communications System (JWICS); and

- Provided standard lifecycle replacement for Special Purpose Processing Nodes (SPPN) to ensure full functionality of unclassified and classified Local Area Networks (LANs).

The FY 2026 budget of $10.934 million will fund the following efforts:

- Procure the last of five next-generation noble-gas systems and recapitalize one radionuclide particulate system for the Nuclear Arms Control Technology (NACT) program to strengthen arms control and
improve the U.S. International Monitoring System (IMS);

- Modernize the Defense Stockpile Management System (DSMS) network infrastructure with advanced network encryption, cyber and Artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities to enhance security and detection
capabilities;

- Complete procurement of Joint Radiation Detection System (RDS) components to support training of Service Members at the DoW Nuclear Weapons School on Kirtland AFB to operate in a realistic combined
joint radiological environment;

- Perform conditions-based technical refresh of Joint Expeditionary Kits (JEKs) to retain working kits for use on a contingency basis;




