 Justification:
 In support of the Secretary of War's Military Defense Strategy, no funding is requested in Fiscal Year (FY) 2027, as the efforts are transitioning to the U.S. Army.

 The FY 2026 discretionary funds provide the procurement of fifty-five (55) THAAD interceptors; obsolescence and modifications; and production support and testing.

 In FY 2025, the MDA received an additional $704.045 million for replacing 56 THAAD interceptors that were expended in support of Israel real world events. The total procurement quantity is 62 THAAD
 Interceptors.

 Historically, MDA successfully used a “synergy” lot buy approach to THAAD Interceptor procurement. This approach entailed awarding a contract that included an option for the following FY funding. By utilizing
 this approach, MDA achieved savings in material costs in multiple FYs. This resulted in a higher Interceptor quantity buy at a lower average unit price than if the lot buys were not combined.

 Interceptor unit costs are heavily dependent on the total quantity being procured in a specific buy and inflation rates. The THAAD Interceptor unit cost is driven by a combination of factors including the production
 of a small quantity of units; the current acquisition strategy to minimize supplier production gaps; and the absence of FMS Interceptor procurement synergy.

 "Procurement Quantity" and "Flyaway Unit Cost" above represent interceptors only, but the "Net Procurement" cost above includes the costs of all hardware. Prior FYs funding included procurement of ground
 components, which affected the "Gross Weapon System Unit Cost".




