 Description:
 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Procurement, Defense-Wide - Counter Small Unmanned Aircraft Systems (C-sUAS) includes $0 thousand of discretionary and $732,000 thousand of mandatory
 (reconciliation) for a total of $732,000 thousand.

 The Joint Interagency Task Force 401 (JIATF 401) is the Department of War (DoW) lead organization for C-sUAS. JIATF 401 synchronizes C-sUAS efforts across the DoW to rapidly deliver joint capabilities at
 scale to defend the homeland, protect US and allied forces, defend critical infrastructure, and assist federal agencies. The task force has a global focus and is a multifaceted organization leading DoW C-sUAS
 activities at the nexus of OSW, the Joint Staff, Combatant Commands, and the Services. The JIATF is innovative, scalable, and threat adaptive. We have one measure of effectiveness: quickly deliver state of
 the art C-sUAS capability to the warfighter at home and abroad. The Secretary of War (SecWar) designated the Secretary of the Army (SA) as the DoW's Executive Agent (EA) for C-sUAS and aligned the JIATF
 401 as a Chairmans Controlled Activity (CCA) in the Joint Staff. The EA holds the acquisition and procurement authority and oversight for the JIATF 401 efforts.

 Our procurement strategy is system-agnostic, focused on acquiring and fielding the most effective capabilities to include commercially available technologies and tech transfers. The funding will be directed
 toward the following key functional areas and system classes:

 I. Detect / Track / Identify ($366.2 million)

 This portion of funding allows JIATF 401 to continue efforts initiated by the Domestic Shield effort. The funds will be used to procure a diverse suite of C-sUAS sensor capabilities to ensure the protection of
 critical fixed-site infrastructure. Procurement will focus on system classes such as:
 • Long-Range Sensors: Including passive Radio Frequency (RF) detection systems for initial warning and cueing.
 • Radars: Advanced solid-state radars (e.g., AESA, MIMO) for high-fidelity tracking of multiple targets.
 • Advanced Identification Solutions: Multi-spectral Electro-Optical/Infrared (EO/IR) systems with integrated video analytics and signature databases to positively identify threats.

 II. Command and Control (C2) ($113.9 million)
 Funding continues the C2 integration for C-sUAS platforms to enhance joint interoperability. These funds will be used to integrate C-sUAS systems into a common C2 solution for the protection of critical sites.
 The effort will focus on establishing:
 • A Common Operating Picture: Software and hardware that fuses sensor data into a single, comprehensive air domain view.


